3. Database Schema
3.1 Tables
Table	Primary Key	Purpose
Users	UserId	Authentication accounts
Items	ItemId	Input/output items with weight & status
ProcessingJobs	JobId	One record per processing action
ItemHierarchy	HierarchyId	Parent-child links between items

3.2 Relationships
•	Items 1→many ItemHierarchy (as parent) — one item can produce many children
•	Items 1→many ItemHierarchy (as child) — a child belongs to exactly one parent
•	ProcessingJobs 1→many ItemHierarchy — one job groups all children created at once
•	Users 1→many Items — creator tracking

3.3 Recursive CTE — GetItemTree
The stored procedure sp_GetItemTree uses a recursive Common Table Expression (CTE) to traverse the parent-child hierarchy to any depth:

WITH ItemTree AS (
  -- Anchor: root items (no parent)
  SELECT i.ItemId, i.Name, i.Weight, i.Status,
         CAST(NULL AS INT) AS ParentItemId, 0 AS Level
  FROM Items i
  WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM ItemHierarchy WHERE ChildItemId = i.ItemId)

  UNION ALL

  -- Recursive: children of already-found rows
  SELECT c.ItemId, c.Name, c.Weight, c.Status,
         h.ParentItemId, t.Level + 1
  FROM Items c
  JOIN ItemHierarchy h ON h.ChildItemId = c.ItemId
  JOIN ItemTree t       ON t.ItemId = h.ParentItemId
)
SELECT * FROM ItemTree ORDER BY Level, Name;

